Netherlands: Parliamentary Elections, 1994-2012

Amber C. Kalb

3/25/2017

The Rise of Right in Netherlands’ Parliament

In the postcolonial era, a national policy of multiculturalism was adopted by the Dutch government after waves of immigration from former colonies, Southern and Eastern European, as well as Middle-Eastern countries, increasingly diversified country’s population. While the 1990’s brought about an emphasis on assimilation policies, Netherlands’ national political of muliculturalism became a point of contention and condestation after the murders of Pim Fortuyn (in 2002) and Theo van Gogh (in 2004). Further compounding xenophobic attitudes in the Netherlands, and the EU in general, was the subsequent Euro and Immigration Crises of 2009 and 2011, respectively. Economic and political turmoil further strained the government’s ability to financially and publically support a national agenda centered on multicultural policies. This eroding popularity of leftist policies is illustrated in the chart below (Figure 1). The following tables chart the Parliamentary elections in the Netherlands for almost two decades (1994-2012) by political alignment and party. For access to the original data see the European Election Database.

From 1994 through 2002, the majority of ballots cast during Dutch Parliamentary elections were overwhelmingly in support of moderate parties (centre, centre-left, centre-right). The 2006 elections mark a definite shift in voter trends away from moderate party alignment in favor of greater support of far-right and far-left factions. This same election year, representation of right-wing parties, by far, the least represented political alignment in the Dutch Parliament, gains a negotiable amount of seats. If we look at figure two below, we can see that the substantial increase in voter support of the far-right is likely due to the emergence of the People’s Freedom Party (PVV) in 2006. While the increasing polarization in ideological alignment through 2010 is not particularly surprising given economic, political and social climate in the Netherlands (see above), the election results in 2012 are.
